org.mellowtech.core.collections.impl

Class BPTreeImp<A,B extends BComparable<A,B>,C,D extends BStorable<C,D>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.mellowtech.core.collections.impl.BPTreeImp<A,B,C,D>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - Wrapped BComparable key class
    B - BComparable key class
    C - Wrapped BStorable value class
    D - BStorable value class
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<KeyValue<B,D>>, BMap<A,B,C,D>, BTree<A,B,C,D>, RangeIterable<KeyValue<B,D>,B>

    public class BPTreeImp<A,B extends BComparable<A,B>,C,D extends BStorable<C,D>>
extends Object
implements BTree<A,B,C,D>
    BPTree is a representation of a minimal BPlusTree. It implements most of the functions in a BPlusTree.

    The BPlus tree structure is suitable for storing large indices on disc. The minimal BPlusTree is divided into two parts (index and key file) with the index and key file divided into blocks. The index contains minimal separator between key blocks and the key file is sorted on key for fast sequential access. Thus, the index only keeps minimal separators between keys, yielding a much more compact index. Depending on the block size the index is more or less deep, however a typical BPlusTree should not reach a depth greater than 3. A resonable blocksize is somewhere between 512-2048 bytes.

    An BPlusTree that can store 512 separators in each block will at worst (i.e maximum height and minimal breath) have 3 levels for an index with 1000000 keys. Thus, at maximum it will only take three disc access for searching a BPlusTree containing 10000000 keys and one additional disc access for retrieving the key. With use of buffers it is often possible to keep portions of the index in memory, yielding much better performance. An LRU cache of size 20 allows for on average less than 1 disc access per search.

    In general, the maximum depth of a BPlusTree is

    d <= 1 + log[m/2]((N + 1)/2)

    where m is the order of the tree and N is the number of keys in the three. Blocks in this BPlusTree is searched binary so that will take:

    log[2](m/2)

    Implementing classes only has to implement three functions searchBlock, insert, and delete (see below). Implementing classes should use the provided functions and fields in this class when implementing the above three functions. The main reason for separating searching, insertion, and deletion from the rest of the functionality is because they can be implemented with various schemes. Especially splitting and merging nodes in the tree can be elaborated with. For a general discussion on BTrees the interested reader should turn to File Structures by Michael J. Folk and Bill Zoellick. Most implementation ideas were taken from that book

    This BPlusTree uses the scheme in com.mellowtech.Disc for disc access. Notably it implements the ByteStorable interface.

      • deleteKeyValue

        protected BPlusReturn<B,D> deleteKeyValue(KeyValue<B,D> key,
                                          int bNo,
                                          int leftNo,
                                          int rightNo)
                                   throws IOException
        Deletes a key/value pair in the key/value file. Deletion can result in one of three things: 1) just delete the key/value, 2) deletion caused an underflow try to redistribute between the left and right block 3) underflow, try to merge block with either the left or right key.
        Case 1 will return: BPlusReturn(BPlusReturn.NONE, deletedKey, null,-1); Case 2 will return: BPlusReturn(BPlusReturn.REDISTRIBUTE, deletedKey, a new separator, either left or right node); Case 3 will return: BPlusReturn(BPlusReturn.MERGE, deletedKey, null, either left or right node);
        Parameters:
        key - the key to delete
        bNo - the physical block number where the key is stored.
        leftNo - the block just left to the current block (i.e just smaller).
        rightNo - the block just right to the current block (i.e just larger.
        Returns:
        depending on what action this delete triggered returns either of three things (see above).
        Throws:
        IOException - if an error occurs

      • handleMerge

        protected void handleMerge(BCBlock<org.mellowtech.core.collections.impl.BTreeKey.Entry<B>,BTreeKey<B>> sb,
                           BPlusReturn<B,D> ret,
                           int cBlock,
                           int pSearch,
                           int pBlock)
                    throws IOException
        Hadles a merge. This could either result in a redistribution of keys, just deletion of the key, or another merge.
        Parameters:

        ret - propagate upwards, containg among things the position of the to be deleted.
        cBlock - the block number for the current sorted block.
        pSearch - the search for the parent key

        Throws:
        IOException - if an error occurs

      • handleRedistribute

        protected void handleRedistribute(BCBlock<org.mellowtech.core.collections.impl.BTreeKey.Entry<B>,BTreeKey<B>> sb,
                                  int cBlock,
                                  BPlusReturn<B,D> ret)
                           throws IOException
        When a deletion caused a redistribution of keys between blocks we could possibly end up having to split the parent node (since keys are variable in size). This method deletes the old separator and add the new separator in a sorted block. It then possible splits the block (and consequently reverts to an insert in the index).
        Parameters:
        sb - the sorted block conting the separator that should be replace.
        cBlock - the physical address of the block.
        ret - the value returned from the underlying deletion...containing notably the new separator and position of the key that should be deleted.
        Throws:
        IOException - if an error occurs
